            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_105wh' title='Col. 105WH &mdash; HC Deb 03 July 2002 vol 388 c105WH' name='column_105wh' href='#column_105wh' rel='bookmark'>105WH</a>
            out leaflets outside the factory gates, only for the director or supervisor to tell employees, when they go inside the factory gates, that if they want to join a particular union the management will help them fill in the forms&#x2014;and then give them their jackets on their way out. That is why only 6.6 million people have joined trade unions in Great Britain&#x2014;they are actively discouraged from joining a trade union because of the fear of being sacked.</p><p>
            The Government have created an environment in which people are happy to join a trade union provided that they do not get the sack for doing so, but it is still important that the Government give some thought to what the trade unions are saying. Trade unions should influence the Government by argument, not through how much money they give the Government, the party or individual Members of Parliament.
